of credit. It is subject to a maximum financial covenant requiring a Consolidated Leverage Ratio of no greater than 3.75 to 1.0 (with temporary increases to 4.25 to 1.0 following qualified acquisitions). \n*   **Maturity Profile:** No debt principal payments are due until August 28, 2027, if the company chooses not to extend. The SpaceX Credit Facility terminates on February 7, 2030.\n*   **Lease Obligations:** Total minimum lease payments were **$5,823 million**, of which $1,026 million is due within the current fiscal year.\n*   **Risks of Indebtedness:** The filing notes that this significant level of indebtedness could adversely affect the business by increasing vulnerability to adverse economic conditions, requiring a substantial portion of cash flow for debt payments, limiting flexibility, and exposing the company to variable interest rate risks.\n\n**Financing Flexibility and Capital Requirements**\n*   **Capital Allocation:** Cash generated from core operations is used to fund R&D projects (like the Starship rocket and next-generation satellites), construct future data centers, and continue expanding AI-enabled products.\n*   **Flexibility to Adjust Spending:** The company retains flexibility to adjust spending across segments. If near-term data center needs decrease or ramp more slowly than expected, it can reduce capital expenditures in that segment and reallocate funds to other business priorities.\n*   **Raising Additional Capital:** The company continually evaluates its cash needs and may raise additional capital or seek alternative financing sources to fund rapid growth. This includes drawdowns on existing or new debt facilities, notes offerings, or bank borrowings. The company may also seek to refinance the SpaceX Bridge Loan or voluntarily repay certain indebtedness early.\n*   **Funding Sufficiency:** The company believes it has sufficient sources of funding to meet its business requirements for at least the next twelve months from the issuance of the consolidated financial statements.\n\n**Cash Flow from Financing Activities**\n*   **Recent Financing Activities:** Net cash provided by financing activities was **$7,125 million** for the three months ended March 31, 2026, and **$26,350 million** for the year ended December 31, 2025. \n*   **Drivers:** The recent increase in financing cash flows was primarily driven by proceeds from the SpaceX Bridge Loan and other AI segment financing arrangements ($17,950 million in Q1 2026; $16,055 million in FY 2025), as well as proceeds from the sale of capital stock ($7,420 million in Q1 2026). These inflows were partially offset by payments on existing debt obligations, debt extinguishment costs, and repurchases of capital stock.',
