        output='# Cash Flow from Operations\n\n## Operating Cash Flow Figures\n\n| Period | Net Cash Provided by Operating Activities |\n|---|---|\n| **Q1 2026** (three months ended March 31, 2026) | **$1,047 million** |\n| **Full Year 2025** (year ended December 31, 2025) | **$6,785 million** |\n\nFor context, Q1 2025 operating cash flow was $727 million, and FY2024 was $5,776 million — so operating cash flow is growing year-over-year.\n\n## Drivers of Operating Cash Flow (per MD&A)\n\n**Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 (+$320 million increase):**\n- Primarily driven by a **$1,153 million increase in deferred revenue** from upfront payments by Space and Connectivity customers\n- Partially offset by lower net income exclusive of non-cash items\n\n**FY2025 vs. FY2024 (+$1,009 million increase):**\n- Higher net income exclusive of non-cash items\n- $1,080 million increase in accounts payable and other liabilities (infrastructure expansion and payment timing)\n- Higher deferred revenue from aviation customer upfront payments\n- Partially offset by a $449 million increase in accounts receivable, prepaid expenses, and inventory\n\n## Free Cash Flow / Gap Between Operating Cash Flow and CapEx\n\nThe filing does **not** explicitly use the term "free cash flow," but the gap between operating cash flow and capital expenditures is stark and clearly disclosed:\n\n| Period | Operating Cash Flow | Capital Expenditures | Implied "Free Cash Flow" |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $1,047M | $10,107M | **$(9,060)M** |\n| FY 2025 | $6,785M | $20,737M | **$(13,952)M** |\n| FY 2024 | $5,776M | $11,163M | $(5,387)M |\n| FY 2023 | $4,520M | $4,415M | $105M |\n\n### Key Observations on the CapEx Gap\n\n1. **CapEx is scaling dramatically faster than operating cash flow.** In Q1 2026 alone, capex ($10.1B) was nearly equal to all of FY2024 ($11.2B) and roughly half of FY2025 ($20.7B).\n\n2. **AI segment is the dominant driver.** The segment-level capex breakdown shows:\n   - Q1 2026 AI capex: **$7,723 million** (76% of total)\n   - FY2025 AI capex: **$12,727 million** (61% of total)\n   - By contrast, Space capex was $1,052M (Q1 2026) / $3,832M (FY2025) and Connectivity was $1,332M / $4,178M.\n\n3. **The gap is financed externally.** With operating cash flow far short of capex, the company has relied heavily on financing activities:\n   - Q1 2026 financing: $7,125M\n   - FY2025 financing: $26,350M\n   - FY2024 financing: $11,830M\n\n4. **Noncash capex also significant.** Supplemental disclosures show additional property, plant, and equipment purchases included in accrued expenses and accounts payable of **$10,649M (Q1 2026)** and **$7,088M (FY2025)**, plus PP&E financed by other financings of $2,684M in Q1 2026 — meaning the total capital investment commitment is even larger than the cash capex figure suggests.\n\n5. **Debt load backing this investment.** As of March 31, 2026, the company had **$29,132 million** in aggregate principal amount of indebtedness outstanding, with no principal payments due until August 2027 (if not extended).\n\n### Summary\n\nThe company is in a heavy investment phase — particularly in AI infrastructure — where operating cash flow, while growing, is dwarfed by capital expenditures. The resulting funding gap (roughly $9B in Q1 2026 alone and ~$14B for FY2025) is being bridged through debt and equity financing rather than internally generated cash, which is typical of an early-stage, capital-intensive growth trajectory but represents a significant cash burn profile.',
